column42:
I wish there was more time spent on the participant's needs - namely RNA-seq, such as a dive into alignment tools, normalization methods, and DE analysis. Or at least a overview of what the workflow might look like for any sequencing experiment. I felt that after discussing about sequencing, I got lost what was next after receiving the FASTQ files. 
I felt that there were too many ad-hoc tools and presentations, and wasn't sure what to make of it.

column41: Enjoyed having an overview of the genomics tools that are available and an explanation of the resources available.I am only recently starting to look into this time of data so it is helpful to know what I can use for help.
column42: I think that more specific sessions would be great in the future. For example a workshop that goes specifically through the steps in sc-sequencing analysis, such as data processing, QC steps, and data visualization steps (the caveats that come with different tools). I think this would be helpful for staff that are not currently in school since it's harder to earn how to do this in a scientifically rigorous way without guided instruction.
I think the hands-on experience is a great way to learn. The only suggestion is to conduct these kind of sessions more often
